results.name: Fibonacci quotients: Fibonacci(p - Legendre(p|5))/p where p runs through the primes.
comment: If p is prime then p divides fibonacci(p - Legendre(p|5)).
The result is known as the Fibonacci Quotient. - _John Blythe Dobson_, Sep 20 2014
Legendre(p|5) = 1 if prime p == 1 or 4 mod 5, -1 if p == 2 or 3 mod 5, 0 if p = 5. - _Robert Israel_, Sep 21 2014
Not to be confused with (Fibonacci(p) - Legendre(p|5))/p, which is A222361. - _Jonathan Sondow_, Dec 08 2017
link: Amiram Eldar, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..647
Zhi-Hong Sun and Zhi-Wei Sun, Fibonacci numbers and Fermat's last theorem, Acta Arithmetica 60(4) (1992), 371-388.
H. C. Williams, Some formulas concerning the fundamental unit of a real quadratic field, Discrete Mathematics, 92 (1991), 431-440.
Jianqiang Zhao, Finite Multiple zeta Values and Finite Euler Sums, arXiv preprint arXiv:1507.04917 [math.NT], 2015.
maple: f:= proc(n) local p; p:= ithprime(n); combinat:-fibonacci(p - numtheory:-legendre(p,5))/p end proc:
